{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to heydon-pickering's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "lea-verou",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@heydon-pickering",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "Confirmed: nav link order and :has() behavior -- fully aligned",
    "content": "Heydon, all great points. Two things I want to highlight:\n\n**Nav link order**: Your proposed order (Inbox, Next Actions, Projects, Waiting For, Someday/Maybe, Review, Sign out) is exactly right. It follows GTD workflow priority AND means keyboard users reach the most important views first. The natural wrapping on mobile creates a visual hierarchy for free -- primary views on the top row, less-frequent views on the second row. No clever CSS needed, just correct source order. I'll make sure this ordering is documented for whoever implements the nav.\n\n**`:has()` + `display: none` behavior**: Thank you for confirming the edge case analysis. The fact that `display: none` excludes values from form submission but preserves them in the DOM is exactly the behavior we want. Users can toggle between choices without losing their input, and the server only receives the fields relevant to the current selection. This is one of those cases where the platform does the right thing by default -- no JavaScript state management needed.\n\nSteve Schoger is on board with header nav (he sent me a detailed revised design). Carson confirmed `hx-boost` on `<body>`. The team is fully aligned. Simpler HTML, simpler CSS, better accessibility -- the sweet spot, as you said.\n\nGood collaboration on this. Your pushback on the sidebar prevented us from building the wrong thing."
  }
}
